library(shiny)
library(shinyjs)

# Define UI with custom styles and shinyjs
ui &lt;- fluidPage(
  useShinyjs(),  # Include shinyjs for dynamic UI updates
  titlePanel("Roll a Six-Sided Die"),

  tags$head(
    tags$style(HTML("
      #roll_button {
        background-color: #3498db;
        color: white;
        font-size: 20px;
        font-weight: bold;
        border-radius: 10px;
        border: none;
        padding: 15px 30px;
        transition: background-color 0.3s;
      }
      #roll_button:hover {
        background-color: #2980b9;
      }
      #die_result {
        font-size: 100px;
        color: #2c3e50;
        font-family: 'Arial', sans-serif;
        text-align: center;
        margin-top: 20px;
        border: 2px solid #34495e;
        border-radius: 10px;
        width: 120px;
        height: 120px;
        display: inline-block;
        line-height: 120px;
      }
    "))
  ),

  sidebarLayout(
    sidebarPanel(
      actionButton("roll_button", "Roll the Die")
    ),
    mainPanel(
      div(id = "die_result", "üé≤")  # Placeholder for die result
    )
  )
)

# Define server logic
server &lt;- function(input, output, session) {
  # Observe button clicks
  observeEvent(input$roll_button, {
    # Show placeholder
    runjs("$('#die_result').html('‚è≥');")

    # Delay for animation
    invalidateLater(10000, session)

    # Update with final die roll
    observe({
      die_roll &lt;- sample(1:6, size = 1)  # Generate random number between 1 and 6
      runjs(sprintf("$('#die_result').html('%d');", die_roll))
    })
  })
}

# Run the application
shinyApp(ui = ui, server = server)

When we implemented rollback on the extensive form version, there was only one NE,

but here there are two:

{Deficit, always High }
{ Balance, (L if B, H if D) }


Both are NE of this game, but the second is a special type of NE
A subgame-perfect Nash equilibrium because it involves the Fed making their rational choice in every subgame.

Solving the Kidnap Game w/ Simultaneous Sugame
Knowing this, what is the NE in the full game?



{ (\(Don't~Kidnap\), \(Kill\)), \(Don't~pay\) }

Shop 1‚Äôs payoff function: \[
\begin{equation*}
  \Pi_1 = [\min\{p_1,p_2\}- 10][100 - \min\{p_1,p_2\}](\frac{1}{2})
\end{equation*}
\] Shop 2‚Äôs payoff function: \[
\begin{equation*}
  \Pi_2 = [\min\{p_1,p_2\}- 10][100 - \min\{p_1,p_2\}](\frac{1}{2})
\end{equation*}
\]

Individual Demand Curves
\[
\begin{equation*}
  D_{JM}(P_{JM},P_{PS}) = \begin{cases}
    100 - P_{JM} & \text{if  } P_{JM} &lt; P_{PS} \\
    \frac{1}{2} (100 - P_{JM}) & \text{if  } P_{JM} = P_{PS} \\
    0 & \text{if  } P_{PS} &lt; P_{JM}
  \end{cases}
\end{equation*}
\]
\[
\begin{equation*}
  D_{PS}(P_{JM},P_{PS}) = \begin{cases}
    100 - P_{PS} & \text{if  } P_{PS} &lt; P_{JM} \\
    \frac{1}{2} (100 - P_{PS}) & \text{if  } P_{PS} = P_{JM} \\
    0 & \text{if  } P_{JM} &lt; P_{PS}
  \end{cases}
\end{equation*}
\]

\(D_{JM}\): quantitiy of subs demanded at Jersey Mike‚Äôs
\(P_{JM}\): price at Jersey Mike‚Äôs, \(P_{PS}\): price at Port of Subs


Notice each shop‚Äôs demand depends on their competitor
Also, to make things easy, this is a symmetric game

Payoff Functions
Jersey Mike‚Äôs profit is price times number of subs: \[
\begin{align}
\Pi_{jm} & = (\text{price} - \text{cost})(\textbf{quantity sold}) \\
      & = (P_{jm} - 10)\mathbf{D_{jm}(P_{jm},P_{ps})} \\
      & = \begin{cases}
      (P_{jm} - 10)(100 - P_{jm}) & \text{if  } P_{jm} &lt; P_{ps} \\
    \frac{1}{2} (P_{jm} - 10)(100 - P_{jm}) & \text{if  } P_{jm} = P_{ps} \\
    0 & \text{if  } P_{ps} &lt; P_{jm}
    \end{cases}
\end{align}
\]

Payoff Functions
Because of symmetry:
Jersey Mike‚Äôs payoff: \[
\begin{equation*}
  \Pi_{jm} = \begin{cases}
      (P_{jm} - 10)(100 - P_{jm}) & \text{if  } P_{jm} &lt; P_{ps} \\
    \frac{1}{2} (P_{jm} - 10)(100 - P_{jm}) & \text{if  } P_{jm} = P_{ps} \\
    0 & \text{if  } P_{ps} &lt; P_{jm}
    \end{cases}
\end{equation*}
\] Port of Subs‚Äôs payoff: \[
\begin{equation*}
  \Pi_{ps} = \begin{cases}
    0 & \text{if  } P_{jm} &lt; P_{ps} \\
    \frac{1}{2} (P_{ps} - 10)(100 - P_{ps}) & \text{if  } P_{jm} = P_{ps} \\
    (P_{ps} - 10)(100 - P_{ps}) & \text{if  } P_{ps} &lt; P_{jm}
    \end{cases}
\end{equation*}
\]

Nash in Sandwich Pricing Game
What is the Nash equilibrium of this game?
\[
\begin{equation*}
